Diseases of globalization
Globalization is being tested as severely as never before.
Everywhere its tensions rumble.
The majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia stagnate or struggle in economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For advocates of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Some regions of the world have gained significant benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
Some regions have however gained only meagre benefits, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The U.S. government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, assert American leaders, is caused by the incompetence of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let us consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that were among the last in international comparisons on the quality of governance of each country (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow faster than countries with small populations.
As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples.
Coastal countries tend to perform better than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries neighboring rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to perform better than countries located far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries pay little attention to these structural issues, the gap between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If rich countries shift the blame onto unlucky countries by claiming they are in some way culturally or politically unsuited to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify the unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than that offered by rich countries, and particularly by America.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the basic needs of the poorest people in the world.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily through better governance within their own country.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to diseases, climatic instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
A candid assessment would indicate further that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds on their own to resolve such problems.
Rather than seeing rich countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most deeply rooted barriers.
A case will strikingly illustrate this situation.
Control of diseases requires a health system capable of providing survival medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount represents only a grain of sand for wealthy countries that systematically spend over $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the capacity of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even though Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases unless it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Rather than condemning the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their growth and economic development.
In some regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity in order to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges relate to disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, more foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems relate to water shortages, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all approach to the Washington Consensus is outdated.
On the eve of the war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blindfolds of the rich and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our shared future depends on it.
